segments.text: He called Jane and me to come to the meeting, and he went through all the awards they had to give, and finally he said, well, I have an apple for the teacher.
And he called my name, and then he called the name of his high school teacher and sent him an apple.
And the high school teacher was at the table I was in,
And after he got back with his apple, he said, well, do you dread being 72 years old?
And I said, well, no, not that.
And I'm not sure I'm telling it just exactly right.
But he looked at me and said, well, do you dread being 72 years old?
And I said, oh, no, I'm already past that.
I'm so and so.
And I just enjoyed the fact that I was older than his high school teacher was.
Did you organize the Campus Young Republicans, or was it already going?
It wasn't going very strong.
I do not have any knowledge of it before
I started working with them.
Describe your work with those, please.
About when was it and how did you get them going?
I have no idea exactly when it was, but somebody came to me and asked me to be an advisor for them.
I don't really know who it was or when.
But I agreed to be an advisor because every organization had to have an advisor.
And if there had been anybody before me, I don't know that.
But I don't take credit for having done it if I, you know, I just don't know.
And I don't really know what year it was.
Among those bright young Republicans, do you remember some names with
Not really.
Was Fred McClure active in the Young Republican?
Not that I remember.
And Rick Perry?
The fact of the matter is, Rick Perry was a Democrat until he ran for Texas Agriculture Commission.
Oh, that's right, that's right.
See, he was a member of the legislature as a Democrat.
He made a nice record for himself.
Did the Young Republicans meet often?
No, they didn't have any scheduled meeting.
Most of the young Republicans would get together when somebody came to the campus that they thought they wanted to hear.
Ford was vice president when he came to the campus at A&M.
I don't remember Reagan coming, but I think he did.
I don't know whether he did or not.
I remember when Vice President Ford came to speak at commencement.
Did you and the group greet him or anything?
I think so.
I really do that.
That was just about all the contact we had.
When...

When Reagan was running for the nomination, I went to the National Republican chairman and told him, and his name was Long, L-O-N-G, told him that Reagan could not carry Texas if Bush wasn't on the ticket.
And I also had contact with another
supporter of Reagan in Houston that I went to see.
And as I say, just like a lot of the other things, I don't know whether I had anything to do with the dog.
But you didn't hurt.
But when you drive from Lubbock over to Midland and talk to a man and say, look here, this is what you need to do, it ought to have some effect.
But I did not believe Reagan could get the nomination without Bush.
Let me add a note in here for the typist.
Typist, this is an editor's note that I want you to add right after the mention of Vice President Ford.
He was scheduled to speak in 1974, I believe it was.
Watergate was at its height, and we were hoping to have him speak at A&M at about the time he was going to become president because Nixon, we knew, wasn't going to be there very long.
I was the chairman of all the commencement arrangements reported to me as dean of faculties.
We were in the letterman's lounge of G. Raleigh White Coliseum, putting on our caps and gowns, getting ready to go into commencement.
And all of us, because of the security arrangements to ensure the safety of the vice president, we all had special little lapel tags, and no one without one of those tags was allowed into the rooms.
Very soon after we all got there, here came a man named M.T.
Harrington, former professor of chemistry and dean and president and chancellor.
And he and Vice President Ford had been on many national committees together, had worked together, were truly old friends.
He didn't have one of those tags.
And the university person checking the door to see that no one was allowed into the letterman's lounge that shouldn't be in there knew Dr. Harrington very well.
And so he didn't turn this retired man away because he didn't have a lapel tag.
And so here came Dr. Harrington striding into the room very rapidly, heading toward Gerald Ford and
with his one hand in his pocket and the other hand reaching out around Vice President Ford's shoulder.
The CIA, or I guess it would be the Secret Service men, did not recognize this man, of course.
They saw that he didn't have a lapel pin as he should have.
They grabbed him and shoved him up against the wall and began to search him.
while the rest of us both frowned and chuckled at the same time.
Ford recognized him quickly and called him by his nickname, and the two of them shook hands, and quickly the Secret Service backed off.
So much for an introduction to Aggie welcomes.
Back now to chatting with you, what was the benefit, you think, in the long run for these young people to be part of the young Republicans while they were undergraduates?
Well, the only benefit that I could see was the fact that we had been the minority party so long and I had suffered so much discrimination without giving up
that I thought they could be indoctrinated to where we'd have some Republican leaders from that group of people.
And I think we have.
Did you have some key faculty and staff allies in those days?
I don't remember but one person that one year Mrs. Black
and I have no idea who she was, came and sort of contested my being an advisor.
And since I had been so long an advisor, she was co-advisor with me for one year.
I don't know the woman.
I don't know anything about her at all.
but she also was recognized as a sponsor for a year.
Now let's see, you were on the faculty about 20 years?
22. Who were the key department leaders during those days in your department, the key faculty and department heads?
Well, since I was in the animal science building, the head of the animal science department was one of the key members of the agricultural faculty.
I knew people in ag education.
You meant O.D.
Butler.
O.D.
Butler.
Describe O.D.
as a department head, his leadership techniques.
I didn't have any contact with him except saying hello to him as he went in and out of the building.
I was in the genetics department with Godby until he retired.
Who succeeded him?
Well, they took the genetics department and divided it into several different sections.
And I was put in the plant science, and somebody else was put in animal science, and somebody else was put over here.
Who headed plant science?
Rossberg.
Describe him as a department leader.
I thought Rossberg was one of the poorest leaders that A&M had.
This is David R-O-S-S-B-E-R-G. That's right.
Who succeeded him?
Uh...
Johan.
Howard Johan.
J-O-H-A-N.
Right.
What about him?
He was a prince.
What made him so capable?
Well, we had a young professor that came into the department after I'd been there for a couple of years.
And his father was a geneticist at Iowa State.
And
He really felt like that being a young man, he just knew more than any old man around there.
And so when I had something that I wanted to discuss with the department head, I'd have to go, I'd talk to him.
And by the time I got to Rossberg's office, Jim
Smith had been there, and instead of listening to me, Rossberg would start telling me what my problem was and how to solve it.
And he had Smith's version only, and that was why I had not very much use for him.
And I'm really baring my soul for you young man.
What about after Rossburg?
I mean, after Johan?
Well, another man took the job after Johan retired.
But I retired the same year Johan retired.
Okay.
All right.
The dean of agriculture, when you came...
I guess was Kunkel, I'm not sure.
No, Patterson or Watkins?
Not the dean of agriculture.
And then Kunkel.
Well, I don't know that.
Okay.
In 57, I don't think that I had either of these other two people, but I'm not going to.
All right.
When the board voted to approve coeducation and make the core optional, what did you and your colleagues think?
Most of us were glad.
We thought it should have been done earlier.
What result did you think it would bring to A&M?
I just thought it would bring growth to the college and some sort of mixing of the sexes that had prevented A&M from growing so many years.
One of the things that I can add to it, that I had a daughter that graduated
And she couldn't go to A&M and she got her degree from TWU.
And I had another daughter that couldn't go to A&M who had to go to Abilene Christian College.
And after they opened A&M to girls, she was taking courses in the summertime at A&M and going to
to Abilene in the long term.
And so she went back to Abilene because she was a leader in Abilene.
And she said, Daddy, they elected me president of the Eta Beta Club.
And I want to go back since I was elected.
I want to go back.
So she went to Abilene two years and went to A&M one year and got her degree from A&M.
And I doubt if there was a
A female got a degree from A&M before Ruth did, except maybe a veterinarian student who was female and admitted before it was open to all females.
Did she ever share any stories about how she was treated as a pioneer co-ed at A&M?
Not particularly.
So you didn't hear of any problems?
She didn't have any problems.
I took a course with her one time.
I generally took a course every two or three years.
I decided that it made you humble if you got in a class.
I took a Spanish class one time that I didn't do well in, and I was ashamed of myself.
I took a psychology class at the same time Ruth took it.
And Ruth would answer the roll,
The teacher would call my name first, Mr. McNeil, and then he'd say, Mrs. McNeil, and Ruth would snort and say, Miss McNeil.
And...

after the course was over with, he said, I didn't know if she wasn't your wife until after she took me quiz and said she beat you a few points and she was so jubilant about it that I realized that it wasn't a wife having fun with her husband.
I don't know what kind of an old goat he thought I was, but anyway, I took a psychology course one time.
Do you remember some of the first coeds you had in class?
Well, one of them was Dr. Deeker's wife, Dr. Deeker's, Paul Deeker's mother.
D-I-E-K-E-R-T.
Right.
And she was a good student.
She made an A, and her son made a B, but he was having to,
do all of the things that he was interested in.
And he had a lab class and he missed a class or two in genetics with outside activity.
Did some faculty members have to change some of their stories and examples when ladies were in the class?
That's right.
Do you remember in your classes, do you remember any pranks that the male students tried to play on the coeds?
I don't remember anything.
I never saw anything.
What about racial integration?
Do you remember any difficulties any black student ever encountered?
No, I don't.
But there weren't many blacks coming.
When the people that I knew in Pakistan came to America on grants, when they came to America at their orientation in Washington,
They'd say, well, what do you want to do?
And at least seven or eight people that I knew over there said, well, we want to go to College Station.
We've got a friend in College Station.
And when they came here and walked on the campus of A&M, one of the first things they noticed was that there was no blacks.
And they said to me, where are the blacks going to school?
And I said, well, they go to school at Prairie View.
It's part of A&M.
And they said, we want to see Prairie View.
And I don't know how many trips I made to Prairie View, taking people from Pakistan down to Prairie View.
And I would go to the president of Prairie View and tell him that we were on the campus.
And Prairie View had a rule that no black people and white people could eat in the dining hall.
And he had asked me to go with the Pakistanis to have our lunch.
And one time I said, Doctor, can't get the name now, Evans.
said, Dr. Evans, I'll go into town.
These people want to eat with you.
And he said, I can't do that.
He said, if I went in there with these people that are considered same as white people, he said, I'd be in trouble.
And I don't know how many people I took to Prairie View that I ate in his place.
I was the host in his place.
Did the Pakistanis ever mention to you any difficulty they had at A&M?
Not really.
I took Kazi to the grocery store every time he went to the store.
I went to
the grocery store one morning, and one of my students was the meat cutter.
And he finished my order, and a woman came up because he was with me.
And so I finished mine.
And this woman stepped up, and he said, is there anything else, Dr. McNeil?
And I said, no, but this man is my friend, and he's going to get his order finished before you can.
I don't have any idea who the woman was, but it was a white woman, I guarantee you.
And there was, that answers your question if I understand it.
Mr. Rutter made these, he led these key changes at A&M.
How did you and your faculty associates come to feel about him and his leadership?
Well, he was much more respected when he left than he was when he came.
What about Jack Williams, who followed him?
Jack Williams was a completely different person, and he was good for A&M.
He's my favorite.
He was good for A&M.
I finally...
said, look here, here I am teaching all of these students and I'm going to find out why I haven't gotten a raise.
And I went to the department head and he said, oh, you know, Jim Smith had been there.
And then I went to Kunkel and he said, well, you haven't done any research work.
I said, you know, research work is important.
And I said, well, I've been teaching students and so on and so on.
And he said, well, I said, if I don't get help from you, I'm going to Williams.
And Williams was really annoyed with me for not stopping because Kunkel told me to stop.
But I told him what I thought, and I didn't lose respect for him at all.
But I did feel like that he had problems.
That's all there is to it.
And then Dr. Williams has the heart attack, and he is replaced then.
He becomes chancellor, and Jarvis Miller became president.
Did you all have any perception of Jarvis as president?
Not any, as far as I'm concerned.
All right, we're getting near the end then.
As you look back over these years...
What were the positive, important decisions that A&M leadership made during your years?
Well, the abolishing core requirement was number one as far as I was concerned.
And the admission of women may have been greater than abolishing the requirement for core.
I don't know that.
but those two things.
And to one extent or another, the only problem that
I was able to find was the fact that the salaries were not really equal.
If you come to the office and waved a telegram in somebody's face, you got a raise, and if you didn't come to the office with a telegram in your hand, they didn't give you a raise.
Are there any omission?
Well, first of all, mistakes.
Can you think of any key decisions that were now we can say were mistakes?
I think it was a mistake to fire Gene Stallings as football coach.
Okay, okay.
I really do.
I was in Dallas when A&M beat Alabama and Bryant carried Gene off the field.
Other mistakes that you can... Any omissions where we had a chance and we just passed it by?
I'm asking things that I really don't have any way of judgment.
And I don't have any to suggest.
All right, who were some people highly deserving of credit that we may have kind of overlooked?
Like you mentioned Howard Gravitt.
Wasn't Howard Gravitt a very capable pre-med advisor?
No question.
I did not question that at all.
No, I know you didn't.
But in the meantime, when I first started teaching, he sent me cards to evaluate the pre-med students.
And it got to be that I had a class of 250 and then another 250 in spring term.
And there was no way for me to evaluate.
Fifteen men out of 250, and I just sent them back to him and said, I can't do it anymore.
I'm not fair.
Couldn't make it.
What about Dean Potts?
I thought Dean Potts did a great job.
I never had any problem as far as I was concerned.
with Posh.
I thought Posh was a fair, level-headed, conscientious man.
Wayne Stark?
I didn't have that much contact with Wayne Stark.
Gordon Gay?
I thought Gordon Gay did a fantastic job.
And the thing that bothers me is the fact that the man who took his place was a CBI man.
And he was there for seventeen years that I didn't know that he had been in CBI.
Now what was his name?
Replace Gordon Gay?
Yeah, Replace Gordon Gay.
He was called a fighting preacher whenever he was in CBI.
And I didn't know him well enough to... All right, if you now could be an advisor to Texas A&M's leadership, what advice would you give them?
Well, the only thing that I would advise...
is that they should give more emphasis to the teaching of young men than to the praise and glory they give to their research people.
And you said men.
You meant men and women.
Well, yes, I did.
So give more credit for teaching than they now give instead of giving so much to research.
That's right.
Any other advice you would give them?
Well, not really.
Let's see.
What have we left out?
I'm about done.
To the end of the ideas I thought.
Well, you've asked an awful lot of things that are in my memoir.
All right.
Let's see.
If you ever have any memorabilia about your A&M experiences that you are going to dispose of, I beg that you please contact the A&M archives because they will preserve them and would be
They will then be a treasure house for everybody to use.
Please don't throw them away.
Let's make believe that somebody walks up to you and gives you a million-dollar check, but the one requirement of that check is that you must pass it on to Texas A&M.
If you could make a substantial gift to Texas A&M, what would you want them to do with that gift?
What purpose would you most want them to accomplish?
Since I was in academics, I want to strengthen the academics rather than the research.
All right.
Where?
How?
Well, give better teachers to the freshmen that come into A&M instead of giving them graduate students to teach classes and do whatever they do.
In any particular discipline?
Not any.
I have no criticism of any department at A&M.
Among your many, many memories of A&M, which ones do you cherish most?
What were the
your happiest A&M moments, proudest?
I guess I'd have to say that it was when I got, was recognized as an outstanding professor in 1965.
And the next one was when I was named as one of the outstanding professors in the School of Arts of
Let me see how that word, the one that Dean, hmm, that word left me too.
Sciences and agriculture and sciences or biology and sciences or something like that.
They started that program in 74.
And four people were recognized.
And the head of the animal science department, Butler, was one of them.
And I do not know all of the others.
John Hutchinson was recognized.
John and I slept in the same room the first year I went to A&M.

He was working on a poultry farm when I was working on the poultry farm And I don't know the other two, but I'm I think they were politicians to tell you the truth and then the next four was McNeil and the publisher of the
Southern agriculture.
I don't remember exactly the name of the magazine, but his name was Scruggs.
And I saw Scruggs and McGregor not too long ago, and I said, well,
